<DOC><DOCNO> AP880722-0087 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0745EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia     07-22 0239</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0244</SECOND><HEAD>Vietnam Moves Up Schedule For Cambodia Withdrawal</HEAD><DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Vietnam's leader, Nguyen Van Linh, saysall Vietnamese troops will leave Cambodia by early 1990 at thelatest instead of the end of 1990 as previously announced.   Linh made the statement in a meeting in Moscow on Thursday withSoviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, according to an officialVietnam News Agency report monitored today in Bangkok.   Soviet-supplied Vietnamese forces invaded Cambodia in late 1978,installed a pro-Vietnamese government and are battling three majorguerrilla groups.   The agency said Linh told Gorbachev that all Vietnamese troops``will be withdrawn by the end of 1989 or early 1990 at the latest,and that the schedule for the troop pullout will be updated if anearly solution is reached.''   Vietnam says it is withdrawing 50,000 troops, or half its forcein Cambodia, this year. It says its military command was withdrawnon June 30 and that the running of the war was turned over to theCambodian government.   The Vietnamese report quoted Linh and Gorbachev as saying theywould strive to create favorable conditions for a settlement andstated that China could contribute to a settlement. China arms theguerrillas.   They also stressed the importance of talks beginning Monday inBogor, Indonesia, that would for the first time bring together allthe warring factions in Cambodia. Vietnamese Foreign MinisterNguyen Co Thach is scheduled to attend the talks.</TEXT></DOC>